Institutional De-Risking and Value Chain Transformation: A Doctoral Research Program on Agricultural Insurance and Smallholder Soybean Resilience in Zambia
The Macro-Economic Imperative and Problem Contextualization
The agricultural landscape of Zambia is navigating a period of profound structural flux, characterized by national development goals set against escalating climatic volatility. Central to this transition is the soybean (Glycine max) sub-sector, which has evolved from a secondary rotation crop into a strategic cornerstone for industrial growth. The Eighth National Development Plan (8NDP) 2022–2026 positions agriculture as a primary driver for Vision 2030, which aspires to transform Zambia into a prosperous middle-income nation.
This doctoral research program is a direct continuation and expansion of my Master’s thesis at the University of Lusaka, titled "Assessing the Impact of Limited Access to Formal Crop Insurance on Smallholder Soybean Farmer Resilience and Value Addition in Eastern Province, Zambia: A Case Study on Strategies for Enhanced Financial Inclusion" (Silungwe, 2026). My previous work established that smallholder soybean producers who cultivate 81% of the total soybean area remain in a state of "uninsured vulnerability" due to an acute insurance gap. The 2023-2024 agricultural season served as a catastrophic validation of this thesis, as El Niño-induced drought decimated 70% of the national harvest, causing soybean production to plummet by 74%.
While my Master's research identified the "What" (the massive awareness gap and high risk-aversion), this doctoral study focuses on the "How" developing a scalable framework for "Institutionalized Risk Finance" to transition farmers from subsistence to resilient agribusiness.
The Research Inquiry: Building from Master's Findings
Building on the results of my Master's thesis, which uncovered a 94% awareness gap and a low mean trust score of 2.68/5 among smallholders, this doctoral inquiry seeks to analyse the causal mechanisms that link insurance to long-term value chain transformation. It moves beyond descriptive barriers to test whether the provision of robust, data-driven insurance can "unlock" capital for mechanized processing, such as oil expellers or specialized storage.
The investigation addresses three specific doctoral-level pillars:
1. Causal Impact Analysis: Moving beyond the "Risk-Aversion Trap" identified in the Master’s study (89.5% of farmers blocked from investment), this phase uses advanced econometrics to quantify how insurance access shifts input intensity and capital expenditure.
2. Institutional Framework Design: Proposing a roadmap for integrating insurance within national programs like CATSP (Comprehensive Agriculture Transformation Support Programme) and FISP (Farmer Input Support Programme).
3. Technological De-Risking: Assessing the use of remote sensing (NDVI) and satellite-derived vegetation indices to reduce "Basis Risk" and lower the high premiums (currently K200–K900 per acre) identified as a supply-side barrier in the preliminary study.
Theoretical Foundations of Risk and Resilience
A rigorous doctoral analysis must engage with the economic theories governing behaviour under uncertainty. This research builds upon the frameworks utilized in the Master’s thesis while adding a layer of structural transformation theory.
The Risk Balancing Hypothesis and Financial Leverage
The Risk Balancing Hypothesis, as detailed by Gabriel and Baker (1980), remains the core theoretical driver. The theory assumes that farmers operate under a maximum acceptable total risk (beta), which is the sum of business risk (BR) and financial risk (FR).
TR = BR + FR
My Master’s findings confirmed a "stagnation equilibrium": because BR remains unmitigated, FR (borrowing) is minimized to near zero. This behaviour is supported by the 2022 MSME Finance Survey, where only 3.3% of Zambian business owners accessed formal credit. This doctoral study will utilize longitudinal data to test if reducing BR through insurance allows for the necessary increase in FR to facilitate value-adding investments.
