New Institutional Economics (NIE) and Transaction Costs
As established in the Master’s study, "market thinness" in rural Zambia is driven by prohibitive transaction costs. The NIE framework, emphasizing the work of Coase and Williamson, helps explain why 94.0% of farmers are unaware of existing products information costs and monitoring costs are too high for traditional indemnity models. The PhD will focus on institutional innovations, such as group aggregation and digital index insurance, to compress these costs.
Socio-Economic Context: The Zambian Soybean Value Chain
The Zambian soybean sector is the country’s second most important crop. While the Master’s thesis focused on the Eastern Province districts of Katete and Petauke, this expansion acknowledges the broader value chain valued at $830 million.
The Master's study noted that the absence of insurance prevents youth Agri entrepreneurs from scaling operations. This continuation integrates findings from FAO/UNIDO (2025) regarding the USD 47.9 million investment needed in soybeans to address the productivity gap.
Proposed Methodology: Doctoral-Scale Analytical Design
To elevate the Master’s work to a doctoral level, the research design has been scaled for higher statistical power and causal identification.
Increased Sample Size and Statistical Power
While the initial Master's study utilized a sample of n=200 to establish baseline correlations, this doctoral continuation increases the sample size to 600 smallholder soybean farmers across the Eastern Province. This increase is essential for performing advanced econometric modelling (IV-Probit) and ensuring sub-regional representativeness across diverse agro-ecological zones.
